[See ProMED-mail Ebola update (96): WHO update, post-Ebola syndrome, vaccine, research 20150809.3567970 for a discussion on the sequelae that people who have had Ebola are encountering. It would be helpful if more details were provided on this case, e.g., has live virus been isolated or only RNA? If the former, then why do the doctors consider infectiousness low? What symptoms was PC experiencing that suddenly led to alarm? PC has said that she has never fully recovered from her ordeal. She has contended with her hair falling out as well as problems with her thyroid (http://www.digitaljournal.com/life/health/ebola-virus-reactivates-in-uk-nurse-condition-is-serious/article/446191).

The only other known case of an individual who ostensibly recovered from disease was Dr. Ian Crozier. In his case, Ebola was found to live undetected inside one of his eyeballs, even though the rest of his body appeared to be clear of virus. Samples from tears and the outer eye membrane tested negative, which meant that the patient was not at risk of spreading the disease during casual contact. This individual also experienced mental and physical sequelae. - Mod.LK]

[And also see: 10 Oct 2015 Dr Ian Mackay's blog
http://virologydownunder.blogspot.com.au/2015/10/is-next-ebola-virus-revelationreactivat.html. This is a long and detailed expert review of the PC case as far as is known to date, with 17 pertinent links. New to me is the information from the family that she had been having hair loss, thyroid problems, and meningitis symptoms previous to this relapse.

ProMED thanks the many subscribers who have sent in dozens of reports on the case. - Mod.JW]

